---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const title = 'Why production voice AI fails after the demo — Jonathan Abraham';
const description = 'The hard part is not the voice. It is state, interruptions, memory, and handoff.';
---
<Base title={title} description={description} showBoot={false}>
  <main id="content" class="doc">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <div class="crumbs">
        <a href="/">~</a><span class="sep">/</span>
        <a href="/#writing">writing</a><span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>voice-ai-after-demo</span>
      </div>
      <div class="prompt">&gt; ./writing/voice-ai-after-demo</div>
      <h1 class="h doc">Why production voice AI fails after the demo</h1>
      <div class="meta-row">
        <span><b>category</b> <span style="color:var(--cyan)">voice_ai_in_production</span></span>
        <span><b>read</b> ~ 7 min</span>
        <span><b>posted</b> 2026-04</span>
      </div>

      <article class="prose">
        <p><strong>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet</strong>, consectetur adipiscing elit. Every voice AI demo is impressive. The model speaks fluently, handles a couple of friendly turns, and the founder claims they've replaced a phone team. Two weeks into production, the same system is silently dropping calls, repeating itself, and confidently inventing customer details.</p>

        <p>The hard part is not the voice. The hard part is everything <em>around</em> the voice.</p>

        <h2>The four things demos hide</h2>

        <h3>1. State across turns</h3>
        <p>Sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. A demo is two or three turns. Production is twenty. State is not "what's in the context window" — it's the operational record that survives a hangup, a redial, and a handoff.</p>

        <h3>2. Interruptions</h3>
        <p>Real callers interrupt. They cough. They turn to talk to someone else. They hang up mid-sentence. Every node in your flow has to be cancellable — not "throw an exception", <strong>cancellable</strong>. Most demos can't even pause cleanly.</p>

        <h3>3. Memory you can audit</h3>
        <p>Duis aute irure dolor in reprehenderit in voluptate velit esse cillum dolore. The moment you put a voice agent in front of a paying customer, "the model said something" stops being acceptable. You need a structured record: what was asked, what was understood, what was decided, what was acted on.</p>

        <h3>4. Handoff</h3>
        <p>The voice agent is rarely the system of record. It's a collector. The handoff to the CRM, the ticketing system, or the human queue has to be <strong>idempotent, retryable, and provenance-tagged</strong>. Most demos handwave this with a webhook.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <b>// rule of thumb</b><br />
          If your demo can't survive being interrupted, redialled, and handed off mid-call, it's not a system. It's a video.
        </div>

        <h2>What I actually do</h2>
        <p>Excepteur sint occaecat cupidatat non proident. I treat the LLM as one node in a graph, not the orchestrator. The graph runs in a real runtime — durable, observable, and boring. The LLM gets called only when it has to be, with a strict schema for what it can return, and a deterministic state machine vetoing anything that violates the call's required fields.</p>

        <p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. The result is slower to build but vastly cheaper to operate, and the conversation with stakeholders shifts from <em>"is the AI good?"</em> to <em>"is the workflow correct?"</em> — which is the question we actually know how to answer.</p>

        <h2>If you're building one</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Write the call as a state machine on paper before you touch a model.</li>
          <li>Make every node cancellable. Test by hanging up at every step.</li>
          <li>Log everything the model said and why. Every field needs a source.</li>
          <li>Treat handoff as a separate, retryable system. Not a callback.</li>
          <li>Demo with hostile callers, not friendly ones.</li>
        </ol>

        <hr />
        <p><strong>Building production voice AI?</strong> <a href="/#contact">I'm available for scoped engagements</a>.</p>

        <div class="pn">
          <a class="pcard next" href="/writing/insurance-intake-design"><small>next note →</small><span>How I would design an AI intake workflow for insurance brokers</span></a>
        </div>
      </article>
